# **Executive Summary** {#executive-summary}

---

ADHD is a condition that affects many children and adults across the planet, and often has a significant detrimental impact on the academic success of those who have it. In particular, children with ADHD struggle greatly thanks to the inherent focus and motivation related challenges associated with the condition. Schooling is incredibly important for children’s development in all aspects of their life, and falling behind academically and emotionally can be a difficult thing to recover from. Children with ADHD have a greater challenge in keeping up with their peers, and supporting them is crucial for their wellbeing as they grow up and move into adulthood. 

Our project contains a convenient collection of countermeasures designed for a child to pick up and use for a few minutes to help them regain focus. The idea at the core of our project is to have our app act as a ‘pit-stop’; It will refuel the user’s dopamine to bring back their motivation, as well as providing an opportunity to take a step away from their struggles and recentre their emotions.

Our target audience is children from the ages of 7-11 years old, but we also have implemented some features for researchers planning on testing with our app that are otherwise hidden from a regular user. As a result, the activity data collected by our app is entirely anonymised. Researchers using our app in a controlled environment will also have access to more granular activity information than our users would see displayed to them, as details such as specific timestamps and usage time are irrelevant to them.

The project itself is designed using React Native as our framework of choice, and is written primarily in TypeScript. We made use of Firebase for our backend, as the data we need to store is very minimal and Firebase fits our small scope better than a more complex solution. Our project’s activities consist of a game, a breathing exercise, and a music player. We also have a stats page that displays a simplified version of the collected data to the user as a form of long-term encouragement. We made an effort to tailor our overall visual and functional design to our target audience as well, emphasising simplicity and clear, understandable graphics to ensure that children as young as 7 years of age will be able to understand and engage with our app.

During development, we managed to reach all of our internal goals according to our schedule, and a barebones MVP was ready for the client at the time we desired. Now, having reached the end of our development cycle, we feel that we have succeeded in our goal of creating an app that will help children take a time-out to deal with their stress or anxiety, or to help them refocus. It also meets our MVP requirement of having functionality that researchers can use to test on children.

As for future plans, we have discussed the possibility of additional features that could make the app more appealing to our target audience, such as more dynamic visuals or adding more game mechanics to improve long-term interest. We also would find smartwatch integration to be a substantially beneficial feature, although this was out-of-scope for our MVP.

# **Introduction** {#introduction}

# ---

Inner Peace is a thoughtfully designed mobile application that aims to be a platform that supports children who have a difficult time focusing due to symptoms of anxiety or ADHD. The primary objective of the app is to provide users with tools that can help them manage their wellbeing by allowing time for them to deal with their stress and refocus themselves. In particular, the target audience of our project are children from 7-11 years old who might have trouble focusing. Therefore, we aimed to design the application in a way that not only appeals to younger audiences but also actively engages them.   
   
The scope of the project includes the development of key features such as games, music and breathing exercises. The game component is intended to provide a burst of dopamine which can effectively help the user to refocus on their work. The music component includes a range of songs that the user can listen to as a chance to have some time out. The breathing component guides the user through a controlled breathing exercise that can help to reduce stress and anxiety. Furthermore, the app includes a stats page that provides users with real time feedback on their progress, thereby motivating users and driving continuous improvement. The app will be available for android platforms with a focus on devices with larger screens such as tablets, although it will also be compatible with smartphones. 

We approached the project with agile project management using the scrum framework. Following this approach, we split the project into different phases called sprints that were a duration of  two weeks. We chose to implement two week sprints because our client meetings were also fortnightly; This was effective as it allowed us to seek feedback from the client at the end of each sprint, thereby enabling us to adapt the project accordingly. This methodology helped us focus on delivering results in a timely manner as we strove for continuous improvement. Furthermore, we employed key tools and technologies including React Native and Firebase to ensure efficient cross-platform functionality and secure data management.

As a result, we have built a functional mobile application that has met key objectives in the successful implementation of the game, music and breathing components. With promising feedback throughout multiple iterations, it shows potential in having an impact on children with anxiety or ADHD. We hope that the app can help children who need assistance refocusing which will ensure that they are not academically disadvantaged.

# **Background** {#background}

---

A recent study found that in the United States between 2020 and 2022, 11.3% of children aged 5–17 years old had been diagnosed with ADHD (Reuben & Elgaddal, 2024). Another study from 2006 showed that up to 80% of children with ADHD reported experiencing academic difficulties (Mayes & Calhoun). These challenges often extend beyond academics and can affect emotional well-being and social development. Given the significant impact ADHD can have on a child's academic performance, our goal for this project was to explore a number of tools to help children that may be struggling in school as a result of ADHD, stress, or anxiety. 

Currently, some existing solutions are available, but are generally targeted towards teens or adults. Because of this they may include more complex elements, such as a more detailed system for reporting feelings, or have more of a focus on staying productive and completing real-world tasks. This complexity can be overwhelming, and these extra features may be irrelevant for younger users. Our app was designed for children around the ages of 7-11 years old, so simplicity is favourable.

It is important to provide care towards those who are struggling in school, especially for students with conditions like ADHD which have symptoms that can directly oppose standard forms of education. Providing care and support to students in this position is critical, not only for their academic success but also for their self-esteem and long-term development. Our project intends to alleviate these symptoms without applying much friction to the education schedule; Each activity in our app is succinct, and using all of them will only take a few minutes in total.

We have 3 core activities \- Whack-A-Mole, box breathing, and a music player. The game is designed to provide a small dopamine boost, which has been shown to help with regaining focus (Koepp et al., 1998; Strahler Rivero T et al., 2015\) Box breathing is a popular and simple breathing exercise that has been shown to aid in calming those who are feeling frustration or irritation (Ashhad, Sufyan et al., 2022). Some styles of music have also been shown to improve clarity and calmness (Shenfield, 2021), so we have included a small selection of music should the user prefer it over box breathing, or would like to use both.

We also make extensive use of a simple Likert scale, which keeps track of how the user is feeling before and after using the above activities. This feeds into the other core feature of our app: A statistics page that reflects the long-term emotional change of the user. Over time, the user should see that their mood has improved and this should act as encouragement and reinforcement. We hope for our app to have a positive impact on our users’ academic success and overall emotional wellbeing.

**User requirements:**

Target Users (Children):

  * Guided Exercises \- The app should provide instructions that guide the user through controlled breathing exercises.  
  * Exercise Duration \- The app should clearly show the duration of the breathing exercise.

  * Likert Scale \- The app should allow users to report their mood before and after an activity using a Likert scale.  
  * Mood Categories \- The app should display mood options that are easy for children to understand.

* Progress Tracking:  
  * Stats Page \- The app should allow for users to view their Likert data on the stats page.

Admin (Lab Users):

* Usage Data Tracking:   
  * Activity Logging \- The app should track activity data for each session.  
  * Admin Access \- The app should allow lab users to view activity data in Firebase Realtime Database for research or analysis.

  * Postcondition: User lands on the main menu with access to all functionalities.

  * Actor \- User

  * Postcondition: The user’s high scores are updated if the current session’s score surpasses the previous high scores.

* Listen to Music:  
  * Actor \- User  
  * Description \- The user can listen to a song of their choice by selecting the music component in the main menu and then choosing their song from the playlist.  
  * Precondition: The music component is available and songs are loaded in the tracklist.  
  * Postcondition: The selected song plays until stopped or another song is chosen.

* Practise Breathing Exercises:  
  * Actor \- User  
  * Description \- The user can practise breathing exercises by selecting the breathing component in the main menu and then following the instructions given for the activity.  
  * Precondition: Breathing component is accessible from the main menu.  
  * Postcondition: Breathing session finishes and the user can choose to return to the main menu or to redo the breathing exercises.

* Report Mood:  
  * Actor \- User  
  * Description \- The user will be able to report their mood before and after an activity, as a Likert scale will pop up before they start the activity and after they complete the activity.  
  * Precondition: User begins or finishes an activity.  
  * Postcondition: Mood data is stored in the database and displayed on the stats page.

* Track Progress:  
  * Actor \- User  
  * Description \- The user can view their Likert data by selecting the stats page in the main menu.  
  * Precondition: User has recorded mood data from previous sessions.  
  * Postcondition: The stats page displays mood data, displaying a trend to the user based on their historical data.

* Track Usage Data:  
  * Actor \- Admin  
  * Description \- Admin can view the activity data by accessing the firebase realtime database.  
  * Precondition: Admin has the necessary permissions to access the Firebase Realtime Database.  
  * Postcondition: Admin views activity data for analysis or reporting purposes.

# **Project Design** {#project-design}

---

## **Technologies used and System architecture**

## **Front End**

We decided to develop our app in Typescript React Native using the Expo framework. We chose to use React Native because it is one of the leading mobile app development frameworks and it has strong cross platform compatibility so it will be easy for our client to build an IOS version if he wants to in the future. We used the expo framework to help speed up development due to its extensive documentation and routing features. Our client wanted us to prioritise developing for Android so we used Android Studio to test and run our app.

## **Back End and Local Storage**

For our local storage we used Expo SQLite. This is a library that allows us to use a SQLite database in the app. We looked into a few other Expo database options and decided that using Expo SQLite made the most sense as it is relatively lightweight and will have better performance as a result. Since we only needed the back end to store the data that app uploads, we chose to use Firebase for our backend. This is because it is easier to set up than other options and Expo has tools to make Firebase integration as simple as possible.

## **Version Control**

We chose to use GitHub as our version control system because our whole team is very familiar with GitHub from using it in other courses. Most of us opted to use GitHub Desktop, as it helped make basic tasks such as committing, switching branches and merging  a lot more straightforward.

## **System Architecture**

Our system is a client server architecture, but is designed to be able to perform almost all functionality offline. Users’ data will not be uploaded to the Firebase realtime database if they are offline, but they can still access any of the core activities.

One aspect of our client side is the content pages which contain assets, typescript, styling and React Native components. This is what the user sees when they are using the app. To switch between pages, we are using Expo Router to seamlessly link pages to each other, similarly to how \<a\> tags work in web applications. The content pages call scripts to handle various logical tasks, such as deciding whether or not to display a Likert scale. These scripts are also what connects the content pages with the local storage by reading or writing data to the Expo SQLite database. In cases where data is read, it can then be returned to the content page to be displayed. There are also a couple of places where the content pages communicate directly with the local storage, such as the stats page.

We also have a function called syncGameData() in one of our scripts that is the sole point of contact between the client side and the server side. This function sends any data that needs to be uploaded to Firebase to be stored in the realtime database. This is a one-way relationship as the app never needs to retrieve any data from the server. To view the data stored in the realtime database, the researchers can access the Firebase directly and download a JSON file containing the data.

![][image3]  
*fig 2: Architecture diagram for our complete system*

![][image4]  
*fig 3: ER diagram for our local storage database*

Our database tables went through a few iterations as we progressed through development. Initially, we just had the *likerts* and *activity\_data* tables. The *likerts* table stores the Likert result (a value from 1-5) and the timestamp, but over time we’ve added other fields such as the day of the week and the timestamp in UTC time to help with getting the stats page graph working correctly. The *activity\_data* table stores the type of activity, start and end timestamps in UTC time and the duration spent on the activity, which is just calculated from the difference between the timestamps. We initially wanted to use the JavaScript Date object and convert it into a readable format for our timestamps. However, this meant that it was being stored as local time which is worse for the researchers looking at the data if the app is being used in multiple countries, so we switched to storing our timestamps in UTC time which is a more standard convention. We realised late in development that it would be better for the researchers looking at the data if they could easily see the change in Likert result with relation to the activity usage data. It would’ve been best to use a foreign key to reference the respective Likert results in the *preActivityLikertResult* and *postActivityLikertResult* fields, but to do this, we would’ve had to redesign our Firebase upload system. Instead, we opted to just store the value of the Likert results in the *activity\_data* table, but in the future it would be good to resolve this properly.

Later, we also added tables for the game scores and user data. The game scores table simply stores the user’s high scores for the game and is limited to the top 5 scores. The user data table stores the last session that was uploaded to Firebase to prevent uploading duplicate data. This table would also allow for adding future fields such as settings to save user settings across different sessions, but our app didn’t end up needing a settings page so this was never implemented.

## **Game Design**

The game is designed around a simple Whack-A-Mole game loop; Moles appear on the screen and the player needs to ‘hit’ them before the moles leave. Our game system spawns a new mole on a 1.25 second interval, and each mole has a visible duration of 2.5 seconds, which is twice the spawn interval. This has the moles visually ‘leap-frog’ each other if the player doesn’t interact with them. This is the regular mole spawning cadence and it does not change throughout the game. To have the game respond to the player’s own pace and avoid the player feeling slowed down by the game, an additional mole is spawned instantly whenever the player hits one. This happens independent of the regular spawn cadence, although the game does have a hard limit of 3 moles visible at any given time, so sometimes a mole will not spawn in order to respect this limit if the player is moving fast enough. This combination of a slow but reliable spawn interval and a responsive player-determined spawn condition makes the game feel consistently engaging at all ranges of player ability and avoids restricting the player’s mechanics as they improve their reaction time and coordination. Additionally, pairing this with a scoreboard system will show more individual improvement over time than if the game had a perfectly consistent pace every time the game was played.

To encourage replayability we decided early on to add a scoring system so that the player retains their interest in the game over a longer period of time, as they will ideally be motivated to try to surpass their best score each time they play. The scoring system makes use of the player-determined pacing, by awarding points based on how quickly you can hit a mole after it first becomes visible. Points are calculated as the inverse percentage of the mole’s visible duration; The longer a mole is visible before being hit, the fewer points are earned. These points are saved as an integer between 0 and 100 to have more variability between attempts, and are added up as the game goes on, which makes it far less likely for the player to get the same score multiple times. The scoring system has been balanced around the idea of having a wide range of possible scores, instead of a simpler system such as earning 1 point for each mole hit within the time limit. The simpler system will have a much smaller and clearer maximum value, and be much harder to continue improving your score once you get close to that limit. The less strict system we have implemented accounts for more intricate details of the player’s performance, such as the speed at which the player hits each mole. Having a higher score ceiling within the same overall game duration will encourage more individual improvement over a longer period of time, as the score limit is much further away and harder to reach.

Another aspect of the scoring system is the combo meter, inspired by similar systems such as the one featured in the *Guitar Hero* series. This mechanic applies a flat multiplier to the points earned from each individual mole and adds an extra way to increase your score and heavily rewards the player’s skill. The combo meter starts at 1x, and increments by 0.2 every time the player manages to hit a mole within the first 30% of its visible duration, up to a maximum of 8x. The combo resets to 1x if the player allows a mole to submerge on its own without being hit. This encourages the player to hit moles as quickly as they can, and rewards them greatly if they manage to hit many moles in a row at a very fast pace. It also promotes some risk/reward for players that are not able to hit moles at a perfect pace; It incentivises hitting the most recent mole first to increase their combo at the risk of ignoring a slightly older mole which may then submerge before being hit and reset the combo entirely. The combo system also helps expand the skill ceiling; As players improve at the game their new scores will be significantly higher than older ones, so their improvement will feel more substantial compared to a system in which the difference between scores are very small.

## **Breathing Design** {#breathing-design}

Initially, we decided to animate a mascot or character breathing in and out in sync with the exercise timing. This choice was driven by our belief that it would create an intuitive visual guide for users, especially for our target audience \- children. We thought that having a character breathe in and out would be easy for kids to follow along with, making the breathing exercise more engaging and enjoyable. In terms of layout, we placed the back button in the top left corner to maintain consistency with the other sections of the app. The mascot's face was centrally positioned, with a timer above it and a start/stop button below. This arrangement was deliberate, as it focused the user's attention on the most important elements of the screen: the character and the controls for the exercise. Additionally, we opted for a blue background because our research showed that blue is widely considered a calming color, which aligned perfectly with the calming and relaxing theme we aimed to establish in the breathing section.

However, after further development, we realized that the character animation was out of scope for the project given the limited amount of development time we had. As a result, we pivoted to a simpler design where a circle expanded and contracted in time with the breathing timer. The circle was meant to symbolically represent lungs, and though it moved us in a more abstract design direction compared to the earlier version, we believed it would still be intuitive for users. The simple visual would guide users through the breathing exercise without the need for a complex animation. The abstract approach allowed us to maintain the functionality and simplicity of the original concept while staying within the project’s technical limitations.

To enhance the aesthetic appeal, we chose an autumn-themed color palette for this version of the page, believing it conveyed a sense of relaxation and comfort. To complement the new theme, we added falling leaves as a subtle background animation which enriched the visual experience. This touch maintained the immersive quality of the app while reinforcing the calming atmosphere we wanted to create in this section.

## **Stats Page Design** 

The statistics page is designed to show long-term improvement for our users by displaying a line graph that represents the change in their reported emotions before and after using our app. We decided to include a graph of the data from the past 7 days, as well as an option to see the entire last month of data. 

For the weekly graph, we discussed whether the data should be displayed with a consistent ordering of Monday on the left and Sunday on the right, but we chose to use a more dynamic display, where the current day is the rightmost data point and the previous 6 days are ordered to the left. This better reflects our intentions with the graph, as it will always have recent data to show rather than appearing blank at the beginning of each week.

We also discussed how the data should be represented in the line graph. Initially, we had the graph display a point for the final Likert response of every session in each day. However, after some user testing we found that having so much information was confusing and not immediately clear about what each point represented. As a result, we decided to only display the final response of the day so that each day on the graph would have exactly one point of data.

In order to test and refine our implementation of these concepts we gathered feedback from user testing and client meetings. Designing the flow of the app was the first part of our UI/UX development process (fig 4 & 5). We used figma to design 2 functional ideations to show to our client. The client feedback and learnings were used to further refine our prototype.

For the activity sections of the app we faced the challenge of keeping the different activities distinct yet cohesive. We achieved cohesion by using the same font and common UI element locations. For example, the back button is consistent across all pages and the instructions align across each page as well. We also used a layered background technique (using progressively brighter/darker colors as the background fades into the distance). These elements help to give the app a similar look and feel while leaving room for thematic differences, using both color and shape.

Each of the app’s 3 activities have a unique theme to keep the activities distinct from each other:

* The play activity (i.e. the game section) features a space theme.  
* The listen activity (i.e. the music action) features a rolling hills theme.  
* The breathe activity (i.e. the breathing section) features an autumn theme.

These themes are reflected in the design of these sections, from assets to colors to backgrounds. There were also many key design considerations that went into the development of the app’s 3 activities. These considerations led to many key design choices. What follows is a list of these key design choices and justifications for each (organised by activity).

Play activity (game):

* The play activity’s UI elements were intentionally placed at the top of the screen, so that the user’s hands won’t cover the UI while playing. If they were placed elsewhere, it would have made the UI difficult to read.  
* While the instructions are displayed,  the background and other presently irrelevant UI elements are dimmed to draw attention to the instructions.  
* The instructions themselves were kept easy to read, and child-friendly.  
* The aliens in the game were chosen as a fun alternative to the traditional moles. This was mostly to avoid potential copyright infringement.  
* The colour of the hammer (in the “alien hitting” animation) was originally red to make it clear and easy to see. However, when getting feedback from the client we discovered it could be seen as a blood splat (*fig 11*). To eliminate this possibility, we changed the colour to a wooden brown.

         

   *fig 11: Old red & new brown hammer*

Listen activity (music):

* A shifting, glowing outline appears around the current track to help the user quickly identify the currently playing song.

Breathe activity (box-breathing):

* The breathe activity also dims the background and inactive UI elements to focus the user's attention on the instructions.  
* The instructions were intentionally placed higher up in the breathing section. This was so they didn’t cover important UI elements, particularly ones  that were being referenced in the instructions. If these UI elements were covered, it could have led to user confusion when the elements suddenly appeared.  
* The instructions in this activity are, again, written with children in mind.  
* Contrast was more of a challenge for the breathing activity than others, we prioritized clear text and legibility over style and looks.  
* Originally we planned to have a breathing face as the centerpiece of the breathing section. However, for [reasons stated previously](#breathing-design), we pivoted to using a simple yet stylish circle design.

The stats page was designed early on. The graph that plots the user’s self-reported mood data takes up most of the screen space. This is to help users assess their long-term mood changes in more detail (*fig 12 & 13\)*.

# **Project Implementation** {#project-implementation}

# ---

## **Local Storage Implementation**

We also implemented a session which tracks each different time the user uses the app. This is just stored as an integer (i.e. 1 for the first time the app is opened) and is saved with the Likert results and activity usage data to differentiate different instances of the app being used.  Towards the end of development, we realised that it would be difficult for the researchers to compare activity usage data to the Likert results because the tables are fully separate. The best solution would’ve been to use a foreign key to reference the Likert scale results from before and after each activity. However, the local storage uses a unique id for each Likert result and when the results get uploaded to Firebase, that id stays the same, meaning that the id is not unique in Firebase as there can be two users uploading Likert results with the same id. To get around this, we decided that the best solution given the limited amount of time left would be to just add the Likert results as a number to the activity usage data objects. This solution, while not quite ideal, saved us from having to fully redesign our upload logic and works well for being able to show the researchers the change in user emotion in relation to how long the user spends on a given activity.

## **Likert Scale Implementation**

Our Likert scale modal was probably the most straightforward section of the app to implement. It is implemented as a React Native modal component with some text and 5 buttons, which when pressed close the modal and save the Likert survey result in the SQLite database. These buttons are different smiley faces, implemented as SVGs and use a custom *LikertButton* component to assist with styling. One issue we faced with it was that we initially wrote the Likert modal component as a class component rather than a functional component. This doesn’t make too much difference, but since class components are no longer recommended by the React developers and since all of our other components are functions, it made sense to change it. The design of the faces also changed over time. Initially, we had the face buttons just as text emoticons, such as “:)”, but we realised later that in the interest of making the faces for the Likert modal and stats page match and keeping the faces centered in their circles, it would be better to implement these as SVGs. This required some styling changes, but overall was not too difficult to change. However, one issue we’ve noticed with this is that on certain virtual device api levels these SVGs appear blurry. Based on our testing on different emulators, this issue will only affect older devices and is possibly just an emulator issue. However, since we don’t have access to lots of different physical devices, we have no way to know for sure.

## **Game Implementation**

To plan the structure and flow of the game, we first made a prototype in the Godot game engine. Using Godot was a good choice for this because it allowed us to work very quickly in figuring out the design of the game. We also explored implementing the Godot version of the game within React Native in order to save a lot of development time and make use of the advanced features that only a bespoke game engine could provide. Unfortunately, after a lot of research and testing, we realised that there is no easy way to integrate a Godot game into a React Native app. The only solution we found was to set up a Node.js server that runs inside the React Native app and serves the game to be run via WebGL. Ultimately, we decided that this would be too time consuming to set up and there would still be a risk of it not working as we hoped. 

Moving forward, we decided to rewrite the prototype of the game in TypeScript underneath the React Native framework for full compatibility with the rest of the project. Initially, we were intending to make use of the ‘react-native-game-engine’ library as it appeared to offer a tidy solution for handling the game loop. We faced issues quite quickly, however, as its documentation was quite limited and many of the features it was built around were not needed for the Whack-A-Mole game structure we were implementing. It also had some performance issues, the game loop would slow down drastically after adding more than a handful of objects. After some struggle, we decided to discard React Native Game Engine and form the game loop using React Native’s hooks.

The main game loop renders 15 moles in an array, and passes properties down to each one depending on the game state so that the moles can be signalled when a game event happens, and vice versa. Each mole is its own functional component, and the core of its logic is a state machine that updates the animation and reflects the visibility of each mole.

On the graphical side, our plan from the beginning was to use sprite-based flipbook animation. The game is quite simple and the objects on the screen did not need to move around, so using this style of animation would fit the game’s structure quite easily. To create the sprites and animations, we created 3D models in Blender and animated the motion using the built-in graph tools. This allowed for quick iteration and adjustments to the specific motion of each animation, and saved a lot of time compared to drawing each frame by hand. Using 3D software also allowed us to experiment with the style of the models. Earlier in development the sprites were rendered with realistic shading, reflections, and glow baked in. As we were finalising the style of the game assets, we experimented with the material shaders to find a rendering style that would better suit the project.

For the technical implementation of the animation, we initially tried two third-party packages for sprite-based animation but one had issues with its dependencies and the other was simply too out-of-date to use. We decided to write our own function to slice the sprite sheets and draw them within a React View object. We also created a JSON file to go alongside the sprite sheet, which provides information on the frame data of each animation the sprite sheet supports. Then, each mole object has its own logic that updates the animation state according to the game state and the frame data found in the JSON file.

## **Music Page Implementation**

The music section is composed of the *TrackList* component and multiple *TrackListItems*. The *TrackList* component is responsible for actually playing the music and contains each *TrackListItem* inside of it in a React Native FlatList component. The *TrackList* uses the ‘expo-av’ library to play and pause the audio and uses a state to keep track of which track is currently playing. We had a bug in this component that caused music to still be playing outside of the music section and wasn’t able to be paused after re-entering the page. To fix this, we used a listener with Expo Router’s navigation  to detect when the user leaves the page. When the user leaves the page, whatever audio was playing at the time gets paused.

Our *TrackListItem* component is the button which tells the *TrackList* to play or pause a track and also contains the logic for whether to display a play or pause button. We wanted to have the border of each track be an animated gradient when the track is playing. To do this we initially tried to use the ‘react-native-animated-border-view’ library, but it doesn’t work with expo so we had to implement the animation ourselves. We did this by placing a linear gradient behind the track and setting the colours of the gradient to all be the same if the track isn’t playing. This acts as the border for our *TrackListItem* component. We set the colours of the gradient to be different when the track is active and we used a useEffect and an interval to change the location of the gradient colours every 100 milliseconds. This makes the gradient shift backwards and forwards while the track is playing. This took a lot of trial and error to get looking smooth, but what we settled on looks quite clean.

## **Breathing Page Implementation**

The original breathing section of our application was implemented using a simple counter mechanism. To initiate the breathing exercise, users would press a button to start the counter, which would increment by one unit every 500 milliseconds. This counting process continued until it reached a value of 32, at which point the counter would reset and begin the cycle again, repeating this pattern until the user manually pressed the stop button. Each number within the range of 0 to 32 corresponded to a specific frame in the animation we had created, effectively syncing the animation with the counter's progress. This approach resulted in the breathing animation resembling a flipbook-style animation, where a series of static images were shown in quick succession to give the appearance of continuous movement. 

Further into development, we wanted to pivot the visual style to be more simplistic and smooth than pixel art and flipbook animation would allow. We decided to use the ‘React Native Reanimated’ library for this. To accommodate this change, we also spent some time revising our breathing-cycle system. The new system has an integer value representing the current breathing state. There are four breathing states and an idle state. We set up a four-second timer using React’s hooks and when the timer finishes the system moves to the next breathing state and the animation is updated accordingly. The new system also allowed for a simple implementation of cyclic repetition, so the whole exercise can repeat a certain number of times before stopping. We added another integer state representing the number of completed repetitions, and when the system reaches the final breathing state it will increment the repetition state and skip the idle state to go back to the first breathing state. If the system has done as many repetitions as the defined maximum repetitions, which is set to four, the breathing state will return to idle instead and the activity will stop.

## **Stats Page Implementation**

The weekly and monthly functionality of the stats page is  implemented with an enum representing the desired display option. We used React’s useEffect hook to re-render the graphs whenever the enum value changes. The value is changed by pressing the toggle button at the top of the page. We used the react-native-segmented-control library for the toggle button.

We implemented the dynamic weekly display by setting the graph’s start date to the current day, and subtracting 6 from the current day for the graph’s end date. These are then passed through to the dynamic weekly data function, and the graphs are drawn, with the data differentiated by a “pre” or “post” condition. We used Expo’s built-in SQLite functionality to query the latest session values from the database. We use the same date variables from the graph display in the SQLite query. We then loop through the result of the query and store the final list of data points to be displayed in the graph. The monthly graph display is implemented very similarly, but using the first and last days of the month as our date range rather than the last 30 days.

We used the ‘react-native-gifted-chart’ library for our graph rendering, and passed in the data sourced from our database. We had an issue with the line interpolation, where the graph would break if the data for the first day was null. To fix this, we added a 0 value to the start and end of our data before passing it into the graph, and the line segment properties are adjusted to be hidden between the first 0 and the next valid data point, as well as from the last valid data point to the last 0\.

During development, we had to change how the date information was being stored. Early on, we had an issue where the SQLite query would mix up the month and day when manually converting to local time, and we also had an issue where the conversion from milliseconds to days would end up being a day behind because of using UTC time. To fix these issues, we decided to simply store the data in UTC time, and only within the stats page we convert to local time using JavaScript’s Date function.

## **Firebase Implementation**

To implement Firebase with our app, we first had to set up and configure a Firebase project in the Firebase console to allow Firebase to integrate to our android app and activate Firebase services. Following this, we had to initialise Firebase in the code and set up a connection to the Firebase realtime database. Once this had been established, we wrote the *syncGameData* script for the purpose of sending data to the realtime database. The script involved fetching activity data from the local storage and then uploading it to the Firebase realtime database. Once data was successfully uploaded, the script would also clear the activity data from the local database. In order to ensure that the script was effectively called upon, we implemented the script in *index.tsx* to ensure that the app prompted data synchronisation regularly.

During the Firebase implementation, we encountered some unforeseen problems in the later stages as we were trying to implement data recovery for the Firebase realtime database. As Firebase’s automated backups feature is behind a paywall, we had to look into an alternative method to allow for automated backups of the realtime database. In particular, we tried to utilise Firebase cloud functions to trigger automated backups of the realtime database. Unfortunately, we were unable to effectively deploy the cloud functions because it turns out that to complete deployment, it also requires Firebase’s paid plan. Hence, at this point we went to seek advice from the client in which he advised us to not worry about automated backups due to the limitations we were bound by.

# **Results & Evaluation** {#results-&-evaluation}

---

Our project goal was to create an innovative application designed to assist children with hyperactivity, as they often face challenges in classroom environments where they struggle to maintain focus, become easily distracted, and may have difficulty staying on task. The application was envisioned as a tool to provide these children with an opportunity to take a break, regain their concentration, and refocus their energy in a more productive way. Our client outlined the specific requirements for the software solution, which included incorporating a guided breathing activity, calming music, and engaging games. Additionally, the client requested the collection of usage data so that the impact of each feature—whether the breathing exercise, music, or games—could be effectively measured and analyzed. These requirements formed the core of the minimum viable product (MVP), and we are pleased to report that we successfully achieved all the primary goals of the project.

We conducted a comprehensive testing process for the system which included local storage testing, backend testing and usage testing.

To ensure the app’s local storage functions as expected, we conducted extensive tests across four key areas:

* User Data  
  * Verified that the *user\_data* table includes the *last\_uploaded\_session* value.  
  * Verified that *last\_uploaded\_session* is set to null if no Likert data has been uploaded.  
  * Verified that *last\_uploaded\_session* accurately reflects the latest session that was uploaded to prevent duplication and maintain consistency.  
* Score Data  
  * Verified that scores can be added to the leaderboard, including edge cases like adding a negative or duplicate score.  
  * Verified the app’s ability to maintain a maximum of five scores, ensuring that a sixth score is only added if it surpasses the existing lowest score.  
  * Verified that if a new high score is achieved, it is highlighted on the leaderboard, while non-high scores do not alter the leaderboard.  
  * Verified that the updateScore function consistently returns scores in descending order.  
* Activity Data  
  * Verified that the *activity\_data* table correctly saves each activity type (game, music, and breathing) with accurate start and end timestamps.  
  * Verified that session numbers increment with each app launch, providing unique identifiers for activity tracking.  
  * Verified that activity data is only saved upon activity completion and is removed from local storage once uploaded to Firebase, preventing redundant data and maintaining storage efficiency.  
* Likert Data  
  * Verified that Likert scale values accurately reflect user selections, with correct session numbers and timestamps for traceability.  
  * Verified that the pre-activity Likert scale is shown only for the first activity of each session and that the post-activity Likert scale is shown after each activity.  
  * Verified that Likert data is categorised correctly as "pre" or "post" based on session timing, allowing for accurate mood tracking before and after activities.

Essentially, for the backend testing, we verified that the activity data and Likert data sent to the Firebase realtime database was accurate and complete. 

For the usage testing, we were only able to externally test the app with our peers because we did not have approval to test the app with our intended audience. Despite this, we wanted to focus on getting feedback on key aspects of the app such as usability and wanted to ensure that the different components of the app were fully functional. In particular, we looked into:

* User Access: Verified that users could access the app and all its functionalities without having to register or log in.  
* Gameplay: Ensured that users can easily navigate to the game and had no issues with the gameplay.  
* Music Listening: Ensured that users can easily navigate to the music section and had no issues with listening to songs.  
* Controlled Breathing Exercises: Ensured that the user can easily navigate to the breathing section and had no issues with following the instructions.  
* Mood Tracking: Verified that the system prompted the users to report their mood before and after activities.   
* Progress Tracking: Verified that the Likert data stored in the local storage and displayed on the graph were complete and accurate.  
* Usage Data Tracking: Verified that the data stored on the Firebase realtime database was complete and accurate.

Upon testing the different components of our system across multiple iterations, we found that there were notable strengths and weaknesses of the system.

Strengths:

* Effective Data Management \- The local storage and backend testing confirmed that the app could effectively manage data and ensure that data was accurate and complete. Moreover, data synchronisation with the Firebase realtime database was consistent and showed that data could be accurately updated in real time.  
* User-Friendly Design \- The app performed well in usability testing as users had no issues navigating to the different components of the app such as the game component, music component, breathing component, and the stats component. In addition to that, the simple and colourful design was a strong point as users who tested the app believed that it would appeal to the target users.  
* Game Component \- The game component was consistently a very well received component of the app through usage testing. Users were highly engaged as they were playing the game and only provided positive feedback on it. Testing was able to confirm great performance and smooth animations for the game. 

Weaknesses:

* Minor Syncing Delays \- While data synchronisation with the Firebase realtime database is generally consistent and reliable, the tests we conducted revealed that there were often delays in updating data to the realtime database. This was especially evident under poor network conditions and as the realtime database became more and more populated with data.  
* Breathing Component \- The breathing component stood out as a weakness throughout the multiple usage testing sessions. Initially, the most common feedback included unclear instructions and unengaging design or implementation. While we did manage to improve the breathing component throughout each iteration, the final iteration still left us with much room for improvement.  
* Stats Component \- The stats component received mixed feedback as users often liked the design but were often left confused with the implementation. Initially, a lot of users had trouble interpreting the data displayed on the graph which made us change the way it was implemented. While we did manage to implement the stats page in a way that clearly displayed the data to users, further feedback indicated a desire for better data visualisation.

# **Future Work** {#future-work}

---

The only client request that we were unable to fulfill was the integration of our application with a smartwatch to monitor users' heart rates while they interact with the app due to limitations with our knowledge of smartwatches as well as our time constraints. Although this feature wasn't included in the current development phase, it holds significant potential for future implementation, as it aligns closely with the client's research objectives. By tracking real-time biometric data such as heart rates, the client could gain valuable insights into user responses and overall engagement, making this an important consideration for future updates.

Although our application is already in a good state, there are still a few more ideas and features we could implement in each section, but because of our limited development time we decided to leave them out of the final product for the time being. 

The inclusion of difficulty settings for the game could be beneficial. Each setting could apply a modifier to certain game parameters, the obvious choice being extending or reducing the duration for which each mole is visible, and the interval between each mole emerging. The current state of the game does match the player’s pace by spawning a new mole as soon as one is hit, but the difficulty settings would realistically be able to account for both slower players and very fast players that may be outside the assumed threshold of reaction time in the base game.

We could also add dynamic visual elements in the game, such as particle effects or animations with more frames. Due to technical constraints around our implementation of the game we decided to keep everything simple and restrict our graphics to pre-rendered sprites, and kept our sprite sheets small to avoid spending too much time manually defining each animation in the JSON file.

It could also be beneficial to add more depth to the graph display, such as allowing users to see the data for every session of each day instead of just the final session. This could be implemented by expanding a portion of the graph when a data point is clicked. We could also add functionality to view data from much further back than just the last week or current month, which may provide more interest in the long-term effects of the app, as it is intended to be the primary long-term reward system of our project.

Furthermore, we would like to add music and some simple music controls to the breathing section, as it feels natural to have some calming audio in the background. We had a simple implementation of this earlier in the development process but decided to cut it due to time constraints, as we couldn’t bring it up to the standard we had achieved in the rest of the app. Another idea we briefly spoke about was a dynamic theme for the page, changing to match the user’s current season. This would add more visual interest but would require a lot of extra art assets, which was out of scope for our project. Lastly, replacing the circle with the counter timer in the middle to a face with breathing cues instead could be more helpful for kids to visualise if they are supposed to breathe in, hold or breathe out.

The music section could also be expanded with a wider range of music from different composers and genres. We would also like to allow the music to continue playing while engaging with other activities, so the user will feel more freedom around their music choice.

# **Conclusion** {#conclusion}

---

The aim of our project was to design and implement a comprehensive software solution to address the academic challenges faced by children with ADHD. After extensive research and consultation, we identified that many children with ADHD struggle not just with focus, but also with managing stress and emotional regulation, which directly impacts their ability to learn and succeed in school. To tackle this, we developed a mobile application that offers a variety of activities designed to provide stress relief and help children refocus their attention. 

Our approach to selecting these tasks was grounded in research and expert advice. We carefully reviewed academic literature on ADHD, focusing on interventions that have been shown to help children manage stress and improve focus. We also worked closely with our client, who has extensive knowledge in the field, to ensure that the activities we included were not only backed by evidence but also were practical and engaging for our target audience. After this consultative process, we decided to implement three key sections within the app: a game, a mindfulness breathing exercise, and a music library. Each of these components was selected for its potential to help children in different ways, whether by providing a dopamine boost, helping them regulate their breathing and calm down, or offering soothing music to relax and unwind.

The game section was designed to be fun and interactive, providing children with a playful way to take a break from their schoolwork. The goal was to create something that would give them a short mental reset, allowing them to return to their tasks with a refreshed mind. The mindfulness breathing exercise was another important part of the app, designed to teach children how to calm their bodies and minds through simple guided breathing exercises. Breathing techniques have been shown to reduce stress and improve focus, making this an essential tool for children with ADHD. Lastly, we included a music library with calming tracks, allowing users to listen to soothing music that can help reduce anxiety and improve concentration.

In terms of design and implementation, we are proud to say that the project was a success. Each section of the app was developed to a high standard, with careful attention to usability, aesthetics, and functionality. The game was engaging and fun to play, the breathing exercise was intuitive and calming, and the music library was well-organized with a range of options for different moods. We also paid special attention to the visual and auditory elements of the app, ensuring that the design was not overly stimulating but rather calming and easy to engage with.

We believe that our app has the potential to make a meaningful difference in the lives of children with ADHD. By providing them with tools to manage stress and improve focus, we hope to contribute to their overall academic success and emotional well-being. Our hope is that, through continued development and feedback, the app can be refined and expanded to offer even more support to the children who need it most.
